[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring method invocation**\n\nI'm considering whether we need to make sure the closure is properly loaded and initialized before calling class$. I wonder if using `MethodHandle` could be clearer than reflection since it might avoid some direct invocation issues. However, Class.forName might still encounter similar problems. \n\nMaybe invoking `org.codehaus.groovy.runtime.InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod` could work since it uses public methods. But, it still feels reflective. I also think about writing a Java helper in a package outside of the library or including a Groovy test source, but there seem to be limitations.\n\n**Revising the approach to closures**\n\nIt seems we should probably avoid using direct `class$` references and instead focus on capturing the closure and invoking `closure.getProperty(\"contentType\")`. I wonder if `javap` shows that GroovyObject uses metaClass to call a generated getter like `getContentType`, which differs from using Class.forName.\n\nHowever, since the call site is class$, perhaps the `class$` helper could be useful for `getContentType` when targeting Java 1.4. But it's puzzling that `javap` can use a class literal for Matcher. Maybe I should leave an explanation while also focusing on the necessary code changes? Analyzing source closure14 maps to contentType(Matcher) against our public API might be a way to improve this.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0aa34280b7ba4278016a27c3914e208196a7026d1e2b36237f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJ8OolsfpOsjHn-kzLOqRuG-tEe9vyc4paL_x2pZquARknV7X8BJDsEtngljsf_r_4jrJbP9LVPEP9Ykb_iKeD8_apjxMcp08QAOmyNAVLl5uS5jmmEzs6jPVFewk1tX_V9R4M96G0ux2w-nVXkmqX9660YCBDD0o5DMjQf6Eh6Tr113LBqJuPu6DH48k1ODIlFTFuv5X7JQyE85AxD6GUZd3-eYoQaYuWzfqHegHgbiOJEmrhBczMbJavRYSExoljupp-BHsday1i48CBIpPNg3PFyThzyhgnExI_zm2N-oAb55Cu5xv_rgcOzcCFzEPTE8y38K8CokBg2VISficCmaf0w